INSERT INTO "sessions" ("id", "user_id", "title", "udate", "duration", "transcript", "summary", "classification", "status", "visuals", "source_type", "source_path", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES
(3, 1, 'FIVE MOST ASKED ESL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS I TIPS AND SAMPLE ANSWERS I ONLINE ESL TEACHING', '2026-01-30 05:09:14', 444, 'Hello, mga kananay. It''s me again, Nanay Jane, and welcome back to our YouTube channel. If you are new to this channel, please consider subscribing and hit the notification bell so that you won''t miss newly posted videos about online teaching, side hustle, and motherhood. You clicked this video because you are an aspiring ESL teacher and you are preparing for an interview. So yeah, this video is really perfect for you. One of the things that makes us feel nervous as applicants is the interview. So for today, we''ll go through the top five most asked ESL interview questions. And hopefully, after watching this, you''ll be more confident in passing your interview in the future. And since I have been with five ESL companies already, which means I have gone through five ESL interviews, I will also share my own answers for your reference. So without further ado, let''s get started. Question number one, could you tell me more about yourself? In this question, mga kananay, the interviewer is not so interested in your slam book kind of answers. So never try to answer it by telling about how you like watching K-dramas and what your zodiac sign is. Although the interviewer has surely read your resume, he or she would still want to hear directly from you about your educational background, your qualities as a person and as a teacher, and of course, your work experience. So you may answer that like this Could you tell me more about yourself My name is Jane I 34 years old and I from Batangas province I am a licensed professional teacher and I''ve been working as an English teacher in grade school for 11 years where I''ve taught ages from 3 all the way up to 12 years old. I''ve been working as a part-time ESL tutor for more than two years now where I''ve handled kids and working professionals. Okay, question number two. What are your strengths? In answering this question, never try to limit your answer to one or two sentences. It''s okay to give just one strength, but make sure to expand upon that and give examples. And don''t forget to connect it with teaching. Remember, you are an ESL teacher applicant and not a contestant in a pageant or any contest. So telling about how friendly you are or how kind you are won''t be enough. so what are my strengths well my biggest strength has to be my passion for teaching i''ve always wanted to be a teacher and i always consider it as my first love so i really love all the things that i do in relation to teaching i do believe that in any kind of job loving what you do is really important for you to work efficiently and effectively there so make it appear that you really want what you''re doing and what you''re getting into so that you will impress the interviewer okay question number three could you tell me about your weakness We all have weaknesses and as the cliche goes nobody perfect But as an applicant, our goal is to impress the interviewer so we could get hired. So when you tell about your weakness, make sure to say it in a way that it also turns out to be your strengths. So how will you answer this or how did I answer this? Well, because I really love teaching, I put 100% dedication to it that sometimes I tend to overwork. It makes me feel exhausted and stressed, but like what I said earlier, I love what I do. So no matter how tired my body is and my mind is, my heart is still happy. Okay, question number four. Why would you like to work for our company? This is one of the most common questions that you will be asked. Among the many ESL companies out there, why do you choose theirs? And this is where the interviewer would check how well you know the company and how eager you are to be a part of it. That is why in my previous videos, I always say do your own research. You have to know the company well before applying. so that when you are asked with this question, you know what to say. And perhaps you may say this. Well, first of all, I prefer teaching Japanese students and your company caters mostly Japanese. And since I a full classroom teacher having a flexible schedule like what your company offers is favorable for me I also heard that teachers receive incentives bonuses and good technical support So there you have to provide information about their company The last question talk about your teaching equipment. Mga kananay, this is something that I won''t answer for you. I won''t give a sample answer because we have different teaching tools and equipment, of course. But I would like you to be prepared in answering questions like, what is your internet service provider or ISP? Do you have a noise-canceling headphone? What are the specifications of your computer? Do you use wired internet connection? Is it fiber or DSL? Do you have a backup in case of power interruption or internet connection problem. So before your interview day comes, make sure that you have all the answers to these questions. And that''s it for now, mga kananay. Thank you so much for staying with me and I hope you find this video helpful. And if you have any questions about ESL interviews, feel free to leave them in the comment section below. And I will also make a content regarding situational questions during interviews. I know many of you are curious also or some are struggling to answer situational questions. So I will make a content on that and I will give you also sample answers or examples on how to answer them. So don''t forget to hit the notification bell. Okay? Thank you so much, mga kananay. Have a good day and I''ll see you in our next vlog. God bless you. Bye!', 'INTRODUCTION TO THE VIDEO\nThe video is an educational content created by Nanay Jane, a licensed professional teacher with 11 years of experience in teaching English to grade school students and 2 years of experience as a part-time ESL tutor. The video is designed to help aspiring ESL teachers prepare for interviews by discussing the top five most asked ESL interview questions.\n\nTOP FIVE MOST ASKED ESL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS\nThe first question is ''Could you tell me more about yourself?'' This question requires the applicant to provide information about their educational background, qualities as a person and teacher, and work experience. The interviewer is not interested in personal hobbies or interests, but rather wants to know about the applicant''s professional background and qualifications.\n\nANSWERING THE QUESTION ''COULD YOU TELL ME MORE ABOUT YOURSELF?''\nNanay Jane provides an example of how to answer this question by sharing her own background, including her age, place of origin, educational background, and work experience. She emphasizes the importance of highlighting one''s professional qualifications and experience in the answer.\n\nTHE SECOND QUESTION\nThe second question is ''What are your strengths?'' This question requires the applicant to provide a detailed answer that highlights their strengths as a teacher. The answer should not be limited to one or two sentences, but rather should provide examples and explanations of how the applicant''s strengths can be applied to teaching.\n\nANSWERING THE QUESTION ''WHAT ARE YOUR STRENGTHS?''\nNanay Jane shares her own answer to this question, highlighting her passion for teaching as her biggest strength. She explains that her passion for teaching enables her to work efficiently and effectively, and that it is essential to love what you do in order to be successful in any job.\n\nTHE THIRD QUESTION\nThe third question is ''Could you tell me about your weakness?'' This question requires the applicant to provide an answer that highlights a weakness, but also shows how it can be turned into a strength. The goal is to impress the interviewer and show that the applicant is self-aware and proactive.\n\nANSWERING THE QUESTION ''COULD YOU TELL ME ABOUT YOUR WEAKNESS?''\nNanay Jane shares her own answer to this question, explaining that her weakness is overworking due to her passion for teaching. She explains that while overworking can lead to exhaustion and stress, her love for teaching keeps her motivated and happy.\n\nTHE FOURTH QUESTION\nThe fourth question is ''Why would you like to work for our company?'' This question requires the applicant to provide an answer that shows they have done research on the company and are genuinely interested in working for them.\n\nANSWERING THE QUESTION ''WHY WOULD YOU LIKE TO WORK FOR OUR COMPANY?''\nNanay Jane emphasizes the importance of doing research on the company before applying. She provides an example of how to answer this question by highlighting the company''s focus on teaching Japanese students, flexible scheduling, and incentives for teachers.\n\nTHE FIFTH QUESTION\nThe fifth question is about the applicant''s teaching equipment. This question requires the applicant to provide information about their internet service provider, computer specifications, and backup plans in case of power or internet interruptions.\n\nPREPARING FOR THE FIFTH QUESTION\nNanay Jane advises applicants to be prepared to answer questions about their teaching equipment by having all the necessary information ready. She encourages applicants to research the company and practice answering common interview questions to increase their confidence and chances of success.\n\nCONCLUSION\nThe video provides valuable information and tips for aspiring ESL teachers to prepare for interviews. By watching the video and following Nanay Jane''s advice, applicants can increase their confidence and improve their chances of success in ESL interviews. Nanay Jane also announces her plan to create content on situational questions during interviews, which will provide further guidance and support for applicants.', 'Educational', 'completed', '[{\"timestamp\":\"00:14\",\"text\":\"[Visual Context at 00:14]\",\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\Ashin\\\\AppData\\\\Local\\\\Te