here like parents, like brothers and sisters, relatives, friends who take on advocacy roles are all examples of informal individual advocacy. So, if ikaw as a student, if you have an advocacy, you may belong here as individual advocacy and you belong here in formal advocacy under individual advocacy. Okay? So, individual advocacy efforts can and do last many years, often in significant isolation. Then we have also voluntary community-based. So it pays staff to advocate for individuals. So in voluntary community-based organizations, so they pay staff or they pay someone to advocate for individuals. individuals. Okay, so you hired, you pay someone to advocate for others or for other individuals. Then we have also citizen advocacy. So when we speak about citizen advocacy, it''s a community-based movement that aims to recognize, promote, and defend the rights, well-being, and interests people with intellectual and or multiple disabilities. Okay, so when we speak about citizen, it''s a community-based movement. Since it is a community-based movement, it promotes and defend the rights not only for a singular person but for many person. Okay? So, the well-being and interest of people with intellectual and or multiple disabilities. So, that''s about for citizen. Okay? So, the aims, the movement that aims to recognize, promote, and defend the rights. For the interest of people. Now, we have also the systems advocacy. So primarily concerned with influencing and changing the system, like the legislation or policy and practices in ways that will benefit people with a disability as a group within society. So if you think that in your barangay or in your current place, if you think that the policy and the practices and the rules are not being exercised well, you may have these systems of focusing in order to influence in changing about the system that being exercised. Especially if the system is not being inclusion. Meaning to say that if the system is may naging, pipilian, or if