t need minimal conflict of interest Guys somehow if you have a conflict of interest with other persons again and again maybe it could be used against you Okay? So baga mamawarayan ka yung paglaong, tungodahan mo, conflict of interest towards other person. Now, third, we have sincerely perceived interests. identifying what is in a person''s interests what we need versus what we want is a difficult process. The advocate does not just speak up for what a person may want or what a person may be interested in. Okay? So that is for sincerely perceived interests. For promotion of person''s welfare, promotion of person''s welfare well-being and justice so as an advocate we do this precisely because the well-being of and justice for disadvantage devalued person is often risk okay so this is naman the goal the goal of advocacy somehow the promotion of person''s welfare. Okay? So we should also promote, we should always promote the welfare of every person, the well-being, and to give justice. Okay? And of course, fifth, vigor of action. So advocacy requires taking a lead, initiating, sense of urgency, challenging the home unity. Okay? Challenging the home unity. Of course, advocacy requires taking a lead. You need to lead, no? You need to take a lead. You need to initiate some programs if you have. You need to have a sense of urgency. Maybe it is urgent to solve the problem as soon as possible That is number five Then of course we have costs It not just the payment itself but it is the cost yung magagasto during the process of advocacy okay It will cost you for you know for other purposes okay so it demands also of some money The cost element of advocacy reflects the demands of all strong advocacy, whether for people with a disability or advocacy for another purpose, like for instance, environmental causes. People with disability need advocates who are prepared and able to be there for a long haul. So that''s about the key elements of a advocacy that you need to consider. Then